argin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Schools are best placed to take a number of positive steps to improve educational outcomes including taking a lead on ‘collaborative influence’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and developing training materials on ‘understanding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the role and influence of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> social networks’.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Talking is a valid catalyst for raising aspirations. Pupils need to be exposed to more catalysts and provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with opportunities to discuss </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ocial network. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Widening participation resources should be more fairly distributed across the education sector. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Targeting disadvantaged students to attend aspiration raising events needs to be reviewed. Too few disadvantaged students attend. Places are un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fairly given to more advantaged pupils.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">powerful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">impact and role of mothers on attainment and aspirations needs to be supported and developed. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> CONTEXT AND BACKGROUND</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission is based on my experience in the following roles and contexts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in relation to the underachievement in education of white working class children.</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Two years experience of as a secondary school teacher in a very large school in Surrey.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Two years experience of as 6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size